			</div>
		</div><!--[BEFORE-ARTICLE]--><span class="marker before-article"></span><section id="ref1" data-level="1"><p class="topic-paragraph"><strong><span id="ref53251"></span>Moscow State University</strong>,  state-controlled institution of higher learning at <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Moscow" class="md-crosslink" data-show-preview="true">Moscow</a>, the oldest surviving, largest, and most prestigious <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/university" class="md-crosslink autoxref" data-show-preview="true">university</a> in <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Russia" class="md-crosslink" data-show-preview="true">Russia</a>. It was founded in 1755 by the linguist <span id="ref53252"></span><a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Mikhail-Vasilyevich-Lomonosov" class="md-crosslink" data-show-preview="true">M.V. Lomonosov</a> and was modeled after German universities, its original faculty being predominantly German.</p><!--[P1]--><span class="marker p1"></span><!--[AM1]--><span class="marker AM1 am-inline"></span><!--[MOD1]--><span class="marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">In the second half of the 19th century, Moscow State University became the most important centre of scientific research and scholarship in Russia. The university underwent a notable expansion following the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/event/Russian-Revolution" class="md-crosslink autoxref" data-show-preview="true">Russian Revolution</a>, and it maintained its preeminent role in mathematics, physics, chemistry, mechanics, astronomy, and other <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="disciplines" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/disciplines" data-type="MW">disciplines</a> during the Soviet period. It presently has more than 350 laboratories, a number of research institutes, several observatories, and also several <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="affiliated" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/affiliated" data-type="MW">affiliated</a> museums. The university’s A.M. Gorky Research Library is one of the largest libraries in Russia. The university has continued to grow and is now housed in new buildings on the Sparrow Hills (formerly Lenin Hills) within Moscow.</p><!--[P2]--><span class="marker p2"></span><!--[AM2]--><span class="marker AM2 am-inline"></span><div class="one-good-fact-module">
</div><!--[MOD2]--><span class="marker MOD2 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">Among Moscow State University’s better-known students were writers <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Mikhail-Yuryevich-Lermontov" class="md-crosslink" data-show-preview="true">Mikhail Lermontov</a>, <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Anton-Chekhov" class="md-crosslink" data-show-preview="true">Anton Chekhov</a>, and <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Ivan-Sergeyevich-Turgenev" class="md-crosslink" data-show-preview="true">Ivan Turgenev</a>, radical <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="intellectuals" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/intellectuals" data-type="MW">intellectuals</a> <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Aleksandr-Ivanovich-Herzen" class="md-crosslink" data-show-preview="true">Aleksandr Herzen</a> and <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Vissarion-Grigoryevich-Belinsky" class="md-crosslink" data-show-preview="true">V.G. Belinsky</a>, and Soviet leader <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Mikhail-Gorbachev" class="md-crosslink" data-show-preview="true">Mikhail Gorbachev</a>.</p><!--[P3]--><span class="marker p3"></span><!--[AM3]--><span class="marker AM3 am-inline"></span><!--[MOD3]--><span class="marker MOD3 mod-inline"></span></section>







